{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1b6f9df6-2944-442e-b926-fedafa86e080","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the breakdown:\n\n## 1. Tests Losing History in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test ID format** to fully qualified names (`Namespace.Class.Method`). Azure DevOps matches tests by ID, so all tests appear \"new.\" You can restore the old IDs by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\nOr, accept the new IDs (recommended long-term) and let history rebuild.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level** context — no test is running yet, so `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it misleadingly returned the name of the first test. Your fix — remove or guard the access:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead if needed\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Other v4 Changes to Watch For\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **Parallel execution** | Now on by default at the **method** level. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or `DoNotParallelize` if tests share state. |\n| **TestContext.Properties** | Read-only in class/assembly init contexts; writes throw. |\n| **Timeout defaults** | `[Timeout]` now applies to the **test method only**, not setup/cleanup. Use `[Timeout(..., CooperativeCancellation = true)]` for cooperative cancellation. |\n| **Assert.AreEqual on doubles** | Floating-point tolerance handling is stricter. |\n| **DataRow / DynamicData** | Display names changed; may also affect DevOps history. |\n\nWould you like me to patch your `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ccda0ec8-305e-4af4-826d-e7dae6434ebe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has MSTest v4 and is experiencing:\n1. Tests appearing as new in Azure DevOps (no history)\n2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]` throwing an exception\n\nLet me provide detailed guidance on these known MSTest v4 breaking changes based on my knowledge.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test ID changes**: MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are generated. The default test ID now uses fully qualified names (namespace + class + method). This causes Azure DevOps to treat them as new tests because the IDs don't match the old ones. This is the \"test history\" issue.\n\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize/ClassCleanup**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a \"class-level\" context, not tied to any specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there's no individual test running at that point — in v3 it would return the first test's name, which was arguably misleading behavior.\n3. There are other breaking changes to be aware of, including how `TestContext` properties are now handled differently in v4.\n\nNow I should provide the user with concrete steps to fix their `SetupTests.cs` file based on these migration issues.","outputTokens":911,"requestId":"1BC1:345713:C0AD8F:D92630:6A03F1CF"},"id":"b4cac76f-3dee-4580-9ac0-70b1d3253e99","timestamp":"2026-05-13T03:37:08.053Z","parentId":"0e7dd8d4-7da3-40ce-9029-c5cf3247a1c0"}
